===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|sheep|lang=enm}}, {{term|scheep|lang=enm}}, {{term|schep|lang=enm}}, {{term|schepe|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|scēap}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*skēpą}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|skiep|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|schäip|lang=frr}} (in the Fering-Öömrang dialect, ''sjep''; in the Sölring dialect, ''sjip''; in the Heligoland dialect, ''skeap''), {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|schaap|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Schaf|lang=de}}), beside {{term/t|gem-pro|*keppôn}} (compare {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|kjappi||he-goat|lang=non}}, dialectal {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Kippe||newborn calf|lang=de}}), of unknown origin. Perhaps from the same {{etyl|xsc|en}} word (compare {{etyl|os|-}} {{term|цӕу|lang=os||goat}}, {{etyl|fa|-}} {{term|چپش||yearling goat|tr=čapiš|lang=fa}})<ref>Vladimir Orel, ''A Handbook of Germanic Etymology'', s.vv. "*keppōn", "*skēpan" (Leiden: Brill, 2003), 213, 340</ref> which was borrowed into {{etyl|sq|-}} as {{term|cjap|lang=sq}}, {{term|sqap|lang=sq||he-goat}} and into Slavic (compare {{etyl|pl|-}} {{term|cap|lang=pl}}).

